within normal limits. There is a 2 cm smooth, firm, mobile swelling on the dorsal aspect of her left wrist. She has full range of movement of the wrist and fingers with normal sensation in the hand.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate definitive management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hydrocortisone injection","Excision","Injection of sclerosant","Digital pressure","Aspiration"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a classic history and examination findings of a ganglion cyst. Ganglion cysts are benign mucin-filled cysts that typically arise from joint capsules or tendon sheaths, most commonly around the wrist.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExcision\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate definitive management as it removes both the cyst and its connection to the joint capsule. This provides the lowest recurrence rate of all treatment options. The procedure is typically performed under local anaesthetic as day surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspiration\u003C/strong\u003E of the cyst contents, while temporarily effective, has a high recurrence rate because the connection to the joint capsule remains intact. The recurrence rate after aspiration is approximately 50%.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydrocortisone injection\u003C/strong\u003E into the cyst, with or without aspiration, does not address the underlying anatomical defect and has similar recurrence rates to aspiration alone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInjection of sclerosant\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended due to the risk of joint damage and a lack of evidence for long-term effectiveness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDigital pressure\u003C/strong\u003E (historically known as \u0027Bible therapy\u0027) involves forcefully rupturing the cyst. This technique is painful, has a high recurrence rate, and risks damage to underlying structures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile some ganglion cysts may resolve spontaneously, surgical excision is indicated when they cause functional impairment, as in this case where the patient\u0027s work is affected.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The definitive treatment of a ganglion cyst is surgical excision including the stalk connecting to the joint capsule.","Ganglion cysts commonly occur at the wrist due to herniation of synovial tissue through the joint capsule.","Conservative treatments including aspiration, steroid injection, and digital pressure have high recurrence rates."],"references":["Zoller SD, Benner NR, Iannuzzi NP. Ganglions in the Hand and Wrist: Advances in 2 Decades. J Am Acad Orthop Surg. 2023;31(2):e58-e67. doi:10.5435/JAAOS-D-22-00105","Gant J, Ruff M, Janz BA. Wrist Ganglions. J Hand Surg Am 2011; 36:510-2. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21371627/","Head L, Gencarelli JR, Allen M, Boyd KU. Wrist ganglion treatment: systematic review and meta-analysis. J Hand Surg Am. 2015;40(3):546-53.e8. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25708437/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67724"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"198"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14560"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14560","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14560"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8524b565-f450-4fc3-8c7a-809a43808d2c.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8524b565-f450-4fc3-8c7a-809a43808d2c.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67724","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67724"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-29T22:32:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-29T22:32:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"198